        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Risk &amp; Sim</strong></td>
          <td>Basic Sensitivity</td>
          <td>Monte Carlo + Scenarios</td>
          <td>12 Simulators + Explicit Risk Objects</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Capital Strategy</strong></td>
          <td>Basic Funding Inputs</td>
          <td>Debt/Equity Modeling</td>
          <td>Intelligent Raise Recommendation &amp; Dilution</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Out-of-Scope for Core v1</h3>
    <p>The following are explicitly deferred to later phases to maintain fo=
cus on the 6=E2=80=9318 month decision window:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Raw Order Transaction Logs (Header/Line level)</li>
      <li>Kitchen Station-level Queueing &amp; Analytics</li>
      <li>Intraday/Hourly Operational Forecasts</li>
      <li>Workforce Scheduling/Rostering</li>
      <li>Real-time Inventory/Recipe-level Decrementation</li>
      <li>Dispatch/Last-mile Logistics Tracking</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>MVP Definition</h3>
    <p>
      The Minimum Viable Product (Phase 1 &amp; 2) includes the complete Pl=
anning Spine, Commercial &amp; Cost Driver Engines,
      and Financial Projection Engine for a single market, enabling end-to-=
end P&amp;L, Cash Flow, and Balance Sheet
      generation with basic scenario comparison.
    </p>

    <h2 id=3D"section-2" class=3D"section-header">2. System Overview and Ar=
chitecture</h2>

    <h3>Finance-First Philosophy</h3>
    <p>The system is built on three pillars:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Driver-Based:</strong> Financial outcomes are calculated fr=
om operational drivers (e.g., Orders * AOV =3D
        Revenue), not manually entered.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Periodized:</strong> Data is organized by Planning Periods =
(Month/Quarter) rather than transaction
        timestamps.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Scenario-Driven:</strong> Every data point exists within a =
Scenario context (Base, Upside, Stress),
        enabling limitless "what-if" modeling without data duplication.
      </li>
    </ol>

